<div class="container text-center" style="background-color:#E9F5FF;">

  <div class="row my-5">

    <div class="col-sm-6 p-3">
      <div class="light-shadow collapse-button" style="background-color: white;">
        <button class="btn btn-block p-4 text-left d-flex" type="button" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#collapse1" aria-expanded="false">
          <div class="h5 mr-auto my-auto font-weight-500" style="font-size: 16px;">Why did we start WunderPass?</div> <div class="ml-auto d-flex rounded js-rotate-if-collapsed" style="width: 32px; height: 32px; background-color:#E9F5FF;">
            <img class="my-auto mx-auto" src="<%= image_path('arrow_down_blue.svg') %>" alt="▼">
          </div>
        </button>
        <div id="collapse1" class="collapse">
          <p class="text-transparent px-4 pt-3 text-left">
            As experienced company founders, we became increasingly aware of how much user data we actually collect and store. The power we had over it seemed to grow disproportionately to the supposed benefit for the user. Although we solely used the data to improve the product at our respective startups, we quickly realized what technical possibilities we increasingly had at our disposal to (hypothetically) use our sovereignty over the data for other purposes.
          </p>
          <p class="text-transparent px-4 pt-3 text-left">
            We don&apos;t believe that this should be the status quo anymore as it almost exclusively leads to a lack of transparency for the user but also for service providers at times.
          </p>
          <p class="text-transparent px-4 pt-3 text-left">
            This is why we put our entrepreneurial spirit and technical understanding - combined as WunderPass - into giving the user back unconditional sovereignty over her data and her digital identity.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="col-sm-6 p-3">
      <div class="light-shadow collapse-button" style="background-color: white;">
        <button class="btn btn-block p-4 text-left d-flex" type="button" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#collapse2" aria-expanded="false">
          <div class="h5 mr-auto my-auto font-weight-500" style="font-size: 16px;">What do we mean by a digital identity?</div> <div class="ml-auto d-flex rounded js-rotate-if-collapsed" style="width: 32px; height: 32px; background-color:#E9F5FF;">
            <img class="my-auto mx-auto" src="<%= image_path('arrow_down_blue.svg') %>" alt="▼">
          </div>
        </button>
        <div id="collapse2" class="collapse">
          <p class="text-transparent px-4 pt-3 text-left">
            In the analog world, we are always clearly recognizable for family members, friends or colleagues. As for strangers, we have been issued with an ID or similar certification that we usually keep close to hand. Online however, we work with a makeshift solution called the "login" by which you have to identify yourself every time with an email address / password combination.
          </p>
          <p class="text-transparent px-4 pt-3 text-left">
            The problems are evident: redundant logins lead to a fragmented and partly inconsistent digital identity, accompanied with an increased risk of data misuse and security gaps. We therefore want to eliminate the outdated "sign-up & login" and replace it with a single, provider independent <em>WunderIdentity</em> that is solely in the interest of the user.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="col-sm-6 p-3">
      <div class="light-shadow collapse-button" style="background-color: white;">
        <button class="btn btn-block p-4 text-left d-flex" type="button" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#collapse3" aria-expanded="false">
          <div class="h5 mr-auto my-auto font-weight-500" style="font-size: 16px;">What can I use WunderPass for?</div> <div class="ml-auto d-flex rounded js-rotate-if-collapsed" style="width: 32px; height: 32px; background-color:#E9F5FF;">
            <img class="my-auto mx-auto" src="<%= image_path('arrow_down_blue.svg') %>" alt="▼">
          </div>
        </button>
        <div id="collapse3" class="collapse">
          <p class="text-transparent px-4 pt-3 text-left">
            It&apos;s our ambitious vision to make WunderPass ubiquitously applicable without the use of any additional codes, passwords or other identifiers. This ensures greater clarity of accounts and prevents identity theft or misuse, while users move frictionlessly through the web.
          </p>
          <p class="text-transparent px-4 pt-3 text-left">
            Our first product focuses on the current daily misuse of our email address as an identifier for the aforementioned "login makeshift solution". The <em>WunderGuard</em> protects your email address, which is a critical part of your digital identity, from unwanted use by supposedly authorized persons or unknown third parties.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="col-sm-6 p-3">
      <div class="light-shadow collapse-button bg-white" style="background-color: white;">
        <button class="btn btn-block p-4 text-left d-flex" type="button" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#collapse4" aria-expanded="false">
          <div class="h5 mr-auto my-auto font-weight-500" style="font-size: 16px;">How does WunderGuard work?</div> <div class="ml-auto d-flex rounded js-rotate-if-collapsed" style="width: 32px; height: 32px; background-color:#E9F5FF;">
            <img class="my-auto mx-auto" src="<%= image_path('arrow_down_blue.svg') %>" alt="▼">
          </div>
        </button>
        <div id="collapse4" class="collapse">
          <p class="text-transparent px-4 pt-3 text-left">
            WunderGuard enables you to pseudonymize your real email address for every online service and hide it as a result. A unique pseudonym is generated automatically for each online service. Thus, you slowly but surely regain control over a part of your identity, including the associated handling of your inbox, as the pseudonyms are fleeting and can be eliminated immediately in the event of any misuse or data leak. The real email address remains hidden and is much less likely to be hacked or leaked.
          </p>
          <p class="text-transparent px-4 pt-3 text-left">
            In addition, the unique pseudonymization of the email address for each online service enables WunderGuard to process inbound emails intelligently - if the user chooses to. WunderGuard could for instance ensure that the user never has to see an invoice again in her inbox. WunderGuard would simply identify the email as such and store the invoice along with the sender&apos;s information in a corresponding folder or cloud storage.
          </p>
          <p class="text-transparent px-4 pt-3 text-left">
            WunderGuard could also summarize emails to its key message by leaving out parts with little informative value. Finally, certain types of emails or even complete pseudonyms could simply be blocked.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

     <div class="col-sm-6 p-3">
      <div class="light-shadow collapse-button" style="background-color: white;">
        <button class="btn btn-block p-4 text-left d-flex" type="button" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#collapse5" aria-expanded="false">
          <div class="h5 mr-auto my-auto font-weight-500" style="font-size: 16px;">Do I have to pay to use it?</div> <div class="ml-auto d-flex rounded js-rotate-if-collapsed" style="width: 32px; height: 32px; background-color:#E9F5FF;">
            <img class="my-auto mx-auto" src="<%= image_path('arrow_down_blue.svg') %>" alt="▼">
          </div>
        </button>
        <div id="collapse5" class="collapse">
          <p class="text-transparent px-4 pt-3 text-left">
            WunderGuard and WunderPass can generally be used free of charge. In fact, users are even incentivized by WunderTokens e.g. for each email address which is replaced with a pseudonym generated by WunderGuard. Or more generally for connecting online accounts to one&apos; WunderIdentity.
          </p>
          <p class="text-transparent px-4 pt-3 text-left">
            The WunderTokens will also be used by connected service providers in the future as a (direct or indirect) means of payment for services. This closes the loop of a token-based ecosystem with an incentive system in which service providers reward the user (in tokens) for releasing user data, which in turn is used to come up with innovative services through more information from connections. This finally results in the user paying for more services (again in tokens).
          </p>
          <p class="text-transparent px-4 pt-3 text-left">
            In this way, sound token economics enables us to guarantee a fair (monetary) distribution of the added value generated by the - whether obvious or subtle, benevolent or malicious - exploitation of user data. A data leech like Google would no longer be the only beneficiary of its services. However helpful their services, their value exclusively stems from something that actually does not belong to them: namely user data.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>

</div>


